  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "The importance of keeping the likelihood of the chosen response in practical applications of large language models, such as reasoning and mathematical problem-solving (Pal et al., 2024; Yuan et al., 2024a), highlights a significant limitation in the applicability of contrastive preference learning.",
    "This raises the following question: Can we design an effective preference optimization algorithm that avoids the Bradley-Terry (BT) assumption?",
    "In this paper, we address this question by proposing a simple yet effective preference optimization algorithm, named InfoPO, which does not rely on the BT assumption.",
    "The key idea of InfoPO is to directly optimize the conditional mutual information between responses and preferences given a prompt.",
    "We first revisit the DPO objective from the perspective of mutual information maximization."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "The importance of keeping the likelihood of the chosen response in practical applications of large language models, such as reasoning and mathematical problem-solving (Pal et al., 2024; Yuan et al., 2024a), highlights a significant limitation in the applicability of contrastive preference learning."
